  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These laws and frameworks are established through international agreements, conventions, and organizations to ensure global cooperation in preventing and prosecuting money laundering activities. Key instruments include:\n\n### 1. **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) (Vienna Convention)**\n   - This is one of the earliest international agreements targeting money laundering. It requires signatory countries to criminalize the laundering of drug-related proceeds and to establish measures to seize and confiscate such assets.\n\n### 2. **United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) (Palermo Convention)**\n   - This convention broadens the scope of anti-money laundering efforts to include proceeds from all serious crimes, not just drug trafficking. It promotes international cooperation in preventing and combating organized crime, including money laundering.\n\n### 3. **United Nations Convention Against Corruption (2003) (Merida Convention)**\n   - This convention focuses on combating corruption and includes provisions to prevent, detect, and prosecute money laundering related to corrupt activities.\n\n### 4. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations**\n   - The FATF is an intergovernmental organization that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats. Its **40 Recommendations** (updated in 2012 and 2018) provide a comprehensive framework for countries to implement effective anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CTF) measures.\n   - The FATF also identifies jurisdictions with weak AML/CTF frameworks through its \"grey list\" and \"black list,\" encouraging global compliance.\n\n### 5. **European Union Directives**\n   - The EU has adopted multiple Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLDs) to harmonize AML laws across member states. The **6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (AMLD6)**, adopted in 2018, strengthens criminal sanctions and extends the scope of predicate offenses for money laundering.\n\n### 6. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**\n   - The Basel Committee, part of the Bank for International Settlements (BIS), has issued guidelines for banks to implement robust AML measures, including customer due diligence (CDD) and reporting suspicious transactions.\n\n### 7. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**\n   - These institutions provide technical assistance and conduct assessments to help countries implement AML/CTF measures, often based on FATF standards.\n\n### 8. **Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs)**\n   - This global network of FIUs facilitates international cooperation in analyzing and sharing financial intelligence to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n### 9. **Regional Organizations**\n   - Regional bodies like the **Asia/Pacific Group on Money Laundering (APG)**, the **Middle East and North Africa Financial Action Task Force (MENAFATF)**, and others work to implement AML standards in their respective regions.\n\n### Enforcement and Compliance\nWhile these international frameworks provide a foundation, enforcement depends on individual countries' implementation. Many nations have enacted domestic laws to comply with these international standards, such as the **USA PATRIOT Act** in the United States and the **Proceeds of Crime Act** in the UK.\n\nIn summary, international laws against money laundering are robust and multilateral, but their effectiveness relies on consistent implementation and enforcement by individual countries.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
